WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.808 --> 00:00:05.730
(dramatic violin music)

2
00:00:14.642 --> 00:00:16.263
<v Voiceover>The miracle doesn't end there.</v>

3
00:00:16.263 --> 00:00:18.531 line:15% 
What happened to the scar tissue?

4
00:00:18.531 --> 00:00:20.263 line:15% 
That's the miracle.

5
00:00:24.043 --> 00:00:26.391
<v Voiceover>There were too many individual circumstances</v>

6
00:00:26.391 --> 00:00:30.086
involved for it to be just a happenstance.

7
00:00:33.825 --> 00:00:34.827 line:15% 
<v Voiceover>Some people might say,</v>

8
00:00:34.827 --> 00:00:36.129
"No, it's not a miracle.

9
00:00:36.129 --> 00:00:38.508 line:15% 
"It's just a coincidence."

10
00:00:38.508 --> 00:00:43.354 line:15% 
But I am convinced that it is an answer to prayer.

11
00:00:45.217 --> 00:00:47.830
<v Voiceover>And I'm thinking, "How can this be?</v>

12
00:00:47.830 --> 00:00:49.483
"This is a joke.

13
00:00:49.483 --> 00:00:51.632
"This does not happen."

14
00:00:52.107 --> 00:00:53.867
<v Voiceover>Regardless of our personal beliefs</v>

15
00:00:53.867 --> 00:00:56.523
about religion or the supernatural,

16
00:00:56.523 --> 00:00:59.061
we all recognize when certain things happen,

17
00:00:59.061 --> 00:01:02.165
that break the rules of everyday life.

18
00:01:02.165 --> 00:01:04.447 line:15% 
When something out of the ordinary happens,

19
00:01:04.447 --> 00:01:07.818 line:15% 
whether you call it a miracle or a coincidence,

20
00:01:07.818 --> 00:01:11.993
it can stop you in your tracks and make you take notice.

21
00:01:14.815 --> 00:01:17.343
(music)

22
00:01:17.343 --> 00:01:20.318
Let's continue examining these phenomenal happenings,

23
00:01:20.318 --> 00:01:24.867
which we began to do in Stories of Miracles part one.

24
00:01:27.422 --> 00:01:29.619
The year was 1950.

25
00:01:29.619 --> 00:01:31.442
Herb Kipf and 13 other singers

26
00:01:31.442 --> 00:01:33.694
in the Westside Baptist Church choir

27
00:01:33.694 --> 00:01:35.496
usually arrived a little early

28
00:01:35.496 --> 00:01:39.133
every Wednesday evening for their 7:30 practice,

29
00:01:39.133 --> 00:01:42.013
but on one memorable night, Herb was running late.

30
00:01:42.013 --> 00:01:45.649
(clock chimes)

31
00:01:45.649 --> 00:01:48.466 line:15% 
<v ->I was at home at that time, writing a letter to our</v>

32
00:01:48.466 --> 00:01:52.462 line:15% 
denominational headquarters in Chicago.

33
00:01:52.462 --> 00:01:54.744
I wanted to get that letter off and drop it in

34
00:01:54.744 --> 00:01:58.200
on the way to choir practice, but I was running out of time.

35
00:01:58.200 --> 00:01:59.427
Finally, I got it done.

36
00:01:59.427 --> 00:02:02.019
So we hurried over as rapidly as we could,

37
00:02:02.019 --> 00:02:06.061
and got there and the Westside was dark.

38
00:02:06.061 --> 00:02:08.727
Completely dark, no lights anyplace.

39
00:02:08.727 --> 00:02:11.266
And I wondered what had happened.

40
00:02:11.266 --> 00:02:15.516
I had to park about a block away from the building, and...

41
00:02:17.111 --> 00:02:19.170
realized that when I got there,

42
00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:22.517
the steeple was lying about where my car was usually parked.

43
00:02:22.517 --> 00:02:27.039
(dramatic music)

44
00:02:27.039 --> 00:02:28.071
Three minutes before the time

45
00:02:28.071 --> 00:02:30.311
for the choir to begin to practice.

46
00:02:31.381 --> 00:02:33.468
Suddenly there was a terrific explosion.

47
00:02:33.468 --> 00:02:36.689
It simply blew apart the entire church.

48
00:02:36.689 --> 00:02:38.652
A gas leak explosion.

49
00:02:38.652 --> 00:02:40.273
The sidewalls were blown out.

50
00:02:40.273 --> 00:02:44.251
The roof and the floor system wound up in the basement,

51
00:02:44.251 --> 00:02:48.251
and surely, nobody could live through something like that.

52
00:02:48.251 --> 00:02:49.454
<v Voiceover>The fire chief immediately</v>

53
00:02:49.454 --> 00:02:51.715
enlisted Herb's help to provide a head count

54
00:02:51.715 --> 00:02:54.030
of any survivors so they could determine

55
00:02:54.030 --> 00:02:56.717
who had been trapped in the rubble.

56
00:02:56.717 --> 00:03:00.174
<v ->I rounded them up, and nobody was missing.</v>

57
00:03:00.174 --> 00:03:02.989
Everybody was there that we were looking for.

58
00:03:02.989 --> 00:03:06.488
Each one of those people was detained just enough

59
00:03:06.488 --> 00:03:08.674
to miss that explosion.

60
00:03:08.674 --> 00:03:11.170
Two little girls, senior high kids, usually

61
00:03:11.170 --> 00:03:14.029
were very prompt, but this particular night,

62
00:03:14.029 --> 00:03:16.076
one of the girls said she wanted to wait

63
00:03:16.076 --> 00:03:18.348
until a program was over.

64
00:03:18.348 --> 00:03:19.938
She wanted to see the finale of a program

65
00:03:19.938 --> 00:03:23.500
that she was interested in, and before the finale came,

66
00:03:23.500 --> 00:03:26.241
the explosion went up.

67
00:03:26.241 --> 00:03:29.078
Another one was my cousin, Harvey.

68
00:03:29.078 --> 00:03:31.180
His wife was out of the town that evening.

69
00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:33.547
She'd taken the little girl along,

70
00:03:33.547 --> 00:03:35.425
but he had two boys and the neighbors

71
00:03:35.425 --> 00:03:38.059
had invited them over for dinner,

72
00:03:38.059 --> 00:03:42.048
and as they sat around, the conversation was good,

73
00:03:42.048 --> 00:03:45.045
the meal was good, and they talked too long.

74
00:03:45.045 --> 00:03:47.819
So, they were late.

75
00:03:47.819 --> 00:03:51.178
There were others who had a story very similar.

76
00:03:52.328 --> 00:03:56.637
While we held hands in a circle, we formed a circle,

77
00:03:56.637 --> 00:03:59.176
and gave thanks for the deliverance that we had had.

78
00:03:59.176 --> 00:04:03.858
Because we realized that a miracle had taken place.

79
00:04:05.288 --> 00:04:09.319
The time was set so accurately because the steeple,

80
00:04:09.319 --> 00:04:13.458
when it fell, also cut the power lines exactly

81
00:04:13.458 --> 00:04:17.351
three minutes before the beginning of the choir practice.

82
00:04:17.351 --> 00:04:19.996
We know that because the clock stopped

83
00:04:19.996 --> 00:04:24.996
at the radio station exactly at 27 minutes after 7 o'clock.

84
00:04:27.697 --> 00:04:30.118
And there are some people who scoff at miracles

85
00:04:30.118 --> 00:04:32.240
because they don't believe it.

86
00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:35.238
"Can't be, it just happened."

87
00:04:35.238 --> 00:04:40.238
But there were too many individual circumstances involved

88
00:04:40.421 --> 00:04:44.906
in that church explosion for it to be just a happenstance.

89
00:04:47.364 --> 00:04:52.308
(soft piano music)

90
00:04:56.599 --> 00:04:59.926
<v Voiceover>Coincidences usually happen unexpectedly,</v>

91
00:04:59.926 --> 00:05:01.548
but some people attribute them

92
00:05:01.548 --> 00:05:04.471
to their own conscious desire or prayer.

93
00:05:04.471 --> 00:05:07.052
In the following story, a mother traces back

94
00:05:07.052 --> 00:05:11.942
an amazing coincidence to a special request she had made.

95
00:05:13.569 --> 00:05:18.155
(music)

96
00:05:18.155 --> 00:05:22.347
<v ->My daughter and her husband, who have two little boys,</v>

97
00:05:22.347 --> 00:05:27.347 line:15% 
had told me that they were vaguely thinking of moving

98
00:05:30.104 --> 00:05:32.349
because their house was a little too crowded

99
00:05:32.349 --> 00:05:35.624
if ever they were to have a third child.

100
00:05:35.624 --> 00:05:40.104
So I had just remembered that, and I thought,

101
00:05:40.104 --> 00:05:42.845
"Oh, well, why don't I go and

102
00:05:42.845 --> 00:05:45.746
"have a look in the neighborhood?"

103
00:05:47.916 --> 00:05:48.706
<v Voiceover>She had driven around</v>

104
00:05:48.706 --> 00:05:50.722
her neighborhood for about an hour when a

105
00:05:50.722 --> 00:05:53.868
white house with black shutters caught her eye.

106
00:05:53.868 --> 00:05:56.225
She remembered seeing it several years earlier

107
00:05:56.225 --> 00:05:58.721
when it had been up for sale, and knew that it would

108
00:05:58.721 --> 00:06:00.769
be perfect for her daughter.

109
00:06:00.769 --> 00:06:04.844
<v ->So I parked in front of it, and I prayed</v>

110
00:06:04.844 --> 00:06:08.233
to the Lord and I thought,

111
00:06:08.233 --> 00:06:13.233
"Lord, I know that what I'm asking is a little silly

112
00:06:13.278 --> 00:06:16.499
"because this house is not for sale.

113
00:06:16.499 --> 00:06:19.219
"Obviously, people are very happy in that house.

114
00:06:19.219 --> 00:06:21.992
"But do you think that, perhaps,

115
00:06:21.992 --> 00:06:24.915
"you could put it on the market?"

116
00:06:24.915 --> 00:06:29.915
Two days later, my daughter called me and she said to me,

117
00:06:30.641 --> 00:06:34.641
"Mom, we have made an offer on a house."

118
00:06:34.641 --> 00:06:37.094
And I said, "Yes, already?

119
00:06:37.094 --> 00:06:39.334
"Did you find something really good?"

120
00:06:39.334 --> 00:06:41.873
And she said, "Yes, I think we did,

121
00:06:41.873 --> 00:06:44.454
"And it's not very far from you."

122
00:06:44.454 --> 00:06:48.570
So I said to her, "It's not far from me? Where is it?"

123
00:06:48.570 --> 00:06:52.229
She said, "Well, it's on the cul-de-sac."

124
00:06:52.229 --> 00:06:54.309
And I said, "On the cul-de-sac?

125
00:06:54.309 --> 00:06:59.238
"You mean, could it be a white house with black shutters?"

126
00:06:59.238 --> 00:07:01.414
And she said yes.

127
00:07:01.414 --> 00:07:05.520
So, I thought, "That must be the house."

128
00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:07.611
It was the house, and I said,

129
00:07:07.611 --> 00:07:11.610
"But, Christine, it's not for sale.

130
00:07:11.610 --> 00:07:15.962
And she said, "It's going to be for sale in two days."

131
00:07:15.962 --> 00:07:20.430
My college roommate lives a few doors from it,

132
00:07:20.430 --> 00:07:24.068
and she told me that the neighbor told her

133
00:07:24.068 --> 00:07:26.990
it was going to be for sale in two days.

134
00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:31.342
So my children were able to buy the house

135
00:07:31.342 --> 00:07:35.868
and now I love to sit on the lawn in front of the house

136
00:07:35.868 --> 00:07:38.450
and look at my grandchildren play

137
00:07:38.450 --> 00:07:41.761
with their new friends on that cul-de-sac.

138
00:07:44.988 --> 00:07:46.449
<v Voiceover>People say that love seems to be</v>

139
00:07:46.449 --> 00:07:48.156
a motivating factor behind the

140
00:07:48.156 --> 00:07:50.577
miracle stories they tell us about.

141
00:07:50.577 --> 00:07:53.830
Love from a friend, love from a parent to a child,

142
00:07:53.830 --> 00:07:56.433
or compassion for a stranger.

143
00:07:56.433 --> 00:07:58.896
<v ->Some people might say, no, it's not a miracle.</v>

144
00:07:58.896 --> 00:08:02.800
It's just a coincidence, but I am convinced

145
00:08:02.800 --> 00:08:06.416
that it is an answer to prayer.

146
00:08:06.416 --> 00:08:09.866
I was not in a terrible need when I prayed.

147
00:08:09.866 --> 00:08:14.866
I wasn't just begging God to meet a need of my children.

148
00:08:15.525 --> 00:08:19.460
It's a prayer that came spontaneously to me

149
00:08:19.460 --> 00:08:22.724
when I was in front of the house.

150
00:08:22.724 --> 00:08:26.096
And that makes me think of the letter

151
00:08:26.096 --> 00:08:29.541
of part of the Corinthian when he says

152
00:08:29.541 --> 00:08:33.594
that we don't know always how to pray,

153
00:08:33.594 --> 00:08:37.136
and that the holy spirit prays for us.

154
00:08:37.136 --> 00:08:41.428
I think the holy spirit put that prayer in my mouth.

155
00:08:43.035 --> 00:08:48.035
(soft flute music)

156
00:08:51.556 --> 00:08:54.758 line:15% 
<v ->I remember a story of a woman who</v>

157
00:08:54.758 --> 00:08:57.942 line:15% 
was very nervous about walking down a bad street,

158
00:08:57.942 --> 00:09:02.304
and she saw a loiterer up ahead.

159
00:09:02.304 --> 00:09:05.664
And she thought, "This guy's bad news."

160
00:09:05.664 --> 00:09:07.936
So she'd been reading a book about angels

161
00:09:07.936 --> 00:09:10.699
and she said, "Oh angels, be with me now,"

162
00:09:10.699 --> 00:09:14.517
which is a very nice way to ask all that's really necessary.

163
00:09:14.517 --> 00:09:19.050
And she went on past this guy and he looked her up and down.

164
00:09:19.050 --> 00:09:20.906
She could feel him sizing her up,

165
00:09:20.906 --> 00:09:24.245
but he didn't do anything to her and she got to the corner

166
00:09:24.245 --> 00:09:27.967
and broke into a run, and got to her home safely.

167
00:09:27.967 --> 00:09:30.590
But the next day she had heard there had been a mugging

168
00:09:30.590 --> 00:09:33.673
around that corner about 10 minutes after she passed

169
00:09:33.673 --> 00:09:35.796
and it was another young woman.

170
00:09:35.796 --> 00:09:39.369
So she put on her red coat, which she always wore

171
00:09:39.369 --> 00:09:41.374
in the winter time and she went off to the police station

172
00:09:41.374 --> 00:09:44.350
and told the police officer what had happened

173
00:09:44.350 --> 00:09:46.910
and he said, "We have that man in custody."

174
00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:48.851
It is the same man.

175
00:09:48.851 --> 00:09:51.550
She looked at him in a lineup, and it was him.

176
00:09:51.550 --> 00:09:55.368
And she told the officer that she was curious

177
00:09:55.368 --> 00:09:59.155
as to why he let her pass, and the officer said

178
00:09:59.155 --> 00:10:01.234
he was too and he would ask the criminal.

179
00:10:01.234 --> 00:10:03.208
And the criminal said, "Oh, yeah, I remember her.

180
00:10:03.208 --> 00:10:04.455
"The one in the red coat."

181
00:10:04.455 --> 00:10:06.372
But he said, "I wouldn't have bothered her

182
00:10:06.372 --> 00:10:08.644
"because she had those two big guys with her,

183
00:10:08.644 --> 00:10:10.532
"one on either side."

184
00:10:10.532 --> 00:10:14.084
So when you hear this story, you gasp and you think,

185
00:10:14.084 --> 00:10:15.672
"Oh, what a wonderful story.

186
00:10:15.672 --> 00:10:17.096
But I thought right away,

187
00:10:17.096 --> 00:10:19.556
what happened to the mugging victim?

188
00:10:19.556 --> 00:10:21.517
Where were her angels?

189
00:10:21.517 --> 00:10:24.313
Now I firmly believe they were right with her.

190
00:10:24.313 --> 00:10:26.830
If I have an angel, then you have an angel.

191
00:10:26.830 --> 00:10:29.571
One of us is not singled out for attention

192
00:10:29.571 --> 00:10:31.310
at the expense of the other.

193
00:10:31.310 --> 00:10:34.819
The question always is, "Why did the angel stop to help

194
00:10:34.819 --> 00:10:36.471
"the woman in the red coat,

195
00:10:36.471 --> 00:10:39.191
"but didn't keep the victim from being mugged?"

196
00:10:39.191 --> 00:10:40.834
It's the age-old question.

197
00:10:40.834 --> 00:10:42.529
We really don't know.

198
00:10:42.529 --> 00:10:45.537
<v ->Why do some people get healed and not others?</v>

199
00:10:45.537 --> 00:10:49.664 line:15% 
Why do some prayers get answered and it seems others don't?

200
00:10:51.144 --> 00:10:55.724
And I don't have a quick answer except to say that

201
00:10:55.724 --> 00:10:59.883
God is not fundamentally in the miracle business.

202
00:10:59.883 --> 00:11:03.756
I will learn to receive what God has to offer,

203
00:11:03.756 --> 00:11:06.977
and not try and put God under my control.

204
00:11:06.977 --> 00:11:08.982
<v ->That's always a very difficult question to answer</v>

205
00:11:08.982 --> 00:11:13.281 line:15% 
and the only answer that I can give is that

206
00:11:14.331 --> 00:11:17.416
we really can't understand the workings of the universe,

207
00:11:17.416 --> 00:11:20.104
the workings of God, and it seems cruel,

208
00:11:20.104 --> 00:11:21.535
sometimes, to think that certain events

209
00:11:21.535 --> 00:11:23.594
might be part of the cosmic plan.

210
00:11:23.594 --> 00:11:27.017
<v ->Sometimes, it may be that God allows difficult things</v>

211
00:11:27.017 --> 00:11:30.591
in our lives in order to bring good out of them later.

212
00:11:30.591 --> 00:11:33.534
<v ->We are not alone in the world, and we,</v>

213
00:11:33.534 --> 00:11:37.560
I think we are part of a huge

214
00:11:37.560 --> 00:11:41.565
tapestry of inter-relations,

215
00:11:41.565 --> 00:11:46.552
and what to us has been terrible hurt

216
00:11:46.552 --> 00:11:51.552
might be working for somebody else

217
00:11:51.615 --> 00:11:53.770
for the best.

218
00:11:53.770 --> 00:11:57.972 line:15% 
<v ->Why does a miracle only have to be a correction,</v>

219
00:11:57.972 --> 00:11:59.477 line:15% 
say, of what we don't like?

220
00:11:59.477 --> 00:12:02.089
Nerves grow back, scars disappear,

221
00:12:02.089 --> 00:12:04.265
fractured skull is no longer there.

222
00:12:04.265 --> 00:12:07.550
Why does that have to be a miracle whereas if another child

223
00:12:07.550 --> 00:12:09.204
still has his fractured skull, how do you know

224
00:12:09.204 --> 00:12:13.566
that isn't going to lead to a miracle, you see?

225
00:12:13.566 --> 00:12:15.656
Because when you stop judging,

226
00:12:15.656 --> 00:12:17.288
you understand what one child said.

227
00:12:17.288 --> 00:12:21.395
He said, "If God took my little friend age six of cancer,

228
00:12:21.395 --> 00:12:23.389
"why did god make her in the first place?"

229
00:12:23.389 --> 00:12:25.853
But then he went on to say, "But maybe her brother

230
00:12:25.853 --> 00:12:30.853
"will become a doctor, see, and maybe that's the miracle.

231
00:12:31.536 --> 00:12:33.488
"What if her brother discovers the cure

232
00:12:33.488 --> 00:12:35.750
"because of his sister?"

233
00:12:35.750 --> 00:12:40.133
<v ->I have to learn not to say, "God, heal my broken arm,"</v>

234
00:12:41.583 --> 00:12:43.856
and get all disappointed and my nose out of joint

235
00:12:43.856 --> 00:12:46.746
if my arm doesn't get healed, but when I do see

236
00:12:46.746 --> 00:12:49.615
God heal someone to get very excited

237
00:12:49.615 --> 00:12:53.726
and rejoice for them and with them.

238
00:12:54.479 --> 00:12:56.164
<v Voiceover>In Joan Wester Anderson's book,</v>

239
00:12:56.164 --> 00:12:59.225
Where Miracles Happen, we hear the story of a man

240
00:12:59.225 --> 00:13:00.996
whose traveling music ministry

241
00:13:00.996 --> 00:13:03.684
brought him a thousand miles from home.

242
00:13:03.684 --> 00:13:06.436
He was at a crossroads in his life, not knowing

243
00:13:06.436 --> 00:13:10.478
if he was really helping anyone and was looking for a sign.

244
00:13:10.478 --> 00:13:13.586
(telephone rings)

245
00:13:14.659 --> 00:13:17.059 line:15% 
<v ->We were traveling as a musical family,</v>

246
00:13:17.059 --> 00:13:20.557 line:15% 
going through Ohio with two big motor coaches,

247
00:13:20.557 --> 00:13:24.386
with our family and some others and a music group

248
00:13:24.386 --> 00:13:28.514
going to churches and conventions and so on.

249
00:13:28.514 --> 00:13:32.258
And I was going through a real trying time in my life

250
00:13:32.258 --> 00:13:37.090
because I was thinking, "Where am I in my life?

251
00:13:37.090 --> 00:13:39.596
"What's going on in my own life?

252
00:13:39.596 --> 00:13:41.482
"I'm telling other people they can have answers.

253
00:13:41.482 --> 00:13:44.948
"Do I really have the answers myself?

254
00:13:44.948 --> 00:13:47.687
"Has God really called me,

255
00:13:47.687 --> 00:13:50.737
"or should I maybe quit and get a job?"

256
00:13:50.737 --> 00:13:55.067
<v ->Even a person as spiritually well-developed</v>

257
00:13:55.067 --> 00:13:59.227
as Ken Gaub still reached a point in his life

258
00:13:59.227 --> 00:14:01.143
where he said, "God, I don't know if

259
00:14:01.143 --> 00:14:03.510
"what I'm doing is the right thing to do.

260
00:14:03.510 --> 00:14:05.110
"Is this pleasing to you?

261
00:14:05.110 --> 00:14:07.511
"I need to know, and I need to know soon.

262
00:14:07.511 --> 00:14:08.492
"I'm burning out.

263
00:14:08.492 --> 00:14:10.444
"Give me a sign."

264
00:14:10.444 --> 00:14:14.358
<v ->These thoughts were going over and over in my mind.</v>

265
00:14:15.428 --> 00:14:18.421
So when everybody went to eat, I stayed in the coach

266
00:14:18.421 --> 00:14:21.780
and sat there a while, and I got thirsty,

267
00:14:21.780 --> 00:14:25.663
so I walked down the street to get a Pepsi,

268
00:14:25.663 --> 00:14:28.820
and I walked back, just slowly, casually,

269
00:14:28.820 --> 00:14:33.820
and I heard a phone ringing, and I listened,

270
00:14:33.865 --> 00:14:36.009
"What is that?"

271
00:14:36.009 --> 00:14:39.123
There was a phone booth near a gas station.

272
00:14:39.123 --> 00:14:42.345
I remember it just rang, rang, rang and rang.

273
00:14:42.345 --> 00:14:44.126
And I thought, "That's odd.

274
00:14:44.126 --> 00:14:46.291
"I wonder why it's ringing like that.

275
00:14:46.291 --> 00:14:48.584
"Maybe it's an emergency or something,

276
00:14:48.584 --> 00:14:50.164
"for somebody close by."

277
00:14:50.164 --> 00:14:52.947
So I went up and just went in the phone booth and

278
00:14:52.947 --> 00:14:55.250
picked up the phone and said, "Hello?"

279
00:14:55.250 --> 00:14:59.506
Operator said, person to person call

280
00:14:59.506 --> 00:15:02.353
for Ken Gaub. (chuckles)

281
00:15:02.353 --> 00:15:03.613
I laughed right out loud.

282
00:15:03.613 --> 00:15:05.564
I said, "You're crazy.

283
00:15:05.564 --> 00:15:06.610
"That's impossible."

284
00:15:06.610 --> 00:15:08.658
And then I thought, I know what it is.

285
00:15:08.658 --> 00:15:13.189
It's candid camera or a set up of some kind.

286
00:15:13.189 --> 00:15:16.453
So I'm looking around, checking my hair and everything.

287
00:15:16.453 --> 00:15:19.588
And I heard somebody saying,

288
00:15:19.588 --> 00:15:22.425
"I believe that's him, I believe that's him."

289
00:15:22.425 --> 00:15:24.622
And the operator said, "Well, is Ken Gaub there?"

290
00:15:24.622 --> 00:15:26.659
And I said, "Yes, I'm Ken Gaub."

291
00:15:26.659 --> 00:15:28.355
She said, "Are you sure?"

292
00:15:28.355 --> 00:15:31.555
I said, "As far as I know, I'm Ken Gaub."

293
00:15:31.555 --> 00:15:34.861
And then the moment I'm talking to this lady,

294
00:15:34.861 --> 00:15:39.861
who in a desperate time had written a suicide note.

295
00:15:40.888 --> 00:15:43.586
<v ->The woman, many, many miles away</v>

296
00:15:43.586 --> 00:15:46.103
who had once seen him on a TV show,

297
00:15:46.103 --> 00:15:50.487
remembered how wonderful his ministry was,

298
00:15:50.487 --> 00:15:53.889
and how he had said just the right things for her that day.

299
00:15:53.889 --> 00:15:58.326
She was suicidal, and thought, "If I could just talk

300
00:15:58.326 --> 00:16:01.505
"to that wonderful man one more time.

301
00:16:01.505 --> 00:16:03.222
"But how would I ever find him?"

302
00:16:03.222 --> 00:16:05.579
And she was given numbers.

303
00:16:05.579 --> 00:16:09.782
She just saw a little collection of numbers in her mind.

304
00:16:09.782 --> 00:16:12.587
She called and gave those numbers to the long distance

305
00:16:12.587 --> 00:16:16.245
operator, who placed the call to the phone booth.

306
00:16:16.245 --> 00:16:19.572
<v ->And I'm thinking, "How can this be?</v>

307
00:16:19.572 --> 00:16:22.676
"What are the odds that somebody calls somebody

308
00:16:22.676 --> 00:16:27.412
"from another state, and it be the right phone number

309
00:16:27.412 --> 00:16:29.215
"and the right guy walking by?"

310
00:16:29.215 --> 00:16:32.158
There, I don't know if the odds are one a billion or what,

311
00:16:32.158 --> 00:16:34.313
but what are the odds of this?

312
00:16:34.313 --> 00:16:37.757
And I talked with her and was telling her that

313
00:16:37.757 --> 00:16:41.694
suicide's not the answer.

314
00:16:41.694 --> 00:16:43.949
Okay, bye bye.

315
00:16:46.056 --> 00:16:48.289
Whew.

316
00:16:48.289 --> 00:16:49.714
<v Voiceover>Ken stayed in contact with the woman</v>

317
00:16:49.714 --> 00:16:53.074
for several months, counseling her regularly until he knew

318
00:16:53.074 --> 00:16:55.794
that her suicidal thoughts were behind her.

319
00:16:55.794 --> 00:16:59.026
And that story kind of took a turn from

320
00:16:59.026 --> 00:17:04.026
me helping this lady to actually God helping me.

321
00:17:05.312 --> 00:17:06.521
Hey, Barbara.

322
00:17:06.521 --> 00:17:08.457
God knows where we are.

323
00:17:10.587 --> 00:17:13.992
<v Voiceover>A woman from Mexico, Teresa Juarez,</v>

324
00:17:13.992 --> 00:17:16.328
tells of an experience in which her doctor

325
00:17:16.328 --> 00:17:20.343
had given up on her, and she was not expected to live.

326
00:17:25.486 --> 00:17:28.295
<v ->(translated) They found a cancerous tumor in my brain.</v>

327
00:17:28.295 --> 00:17:33.201
And the doctor said that this tumor was completely developed

328
00:17:33.201 --> 00:17:35.910
throughout my whole brain.

329
00:17:35.910 --> 00:17:38.385
Those were his words, and he said,

330
00:17:38.385 --> 00:17:41.691
"You won't live for even six months more."

331
00:17:41.691 --> 00:17:44.187 line:15% 
So I felt very upset.

332
00:17:44.187 --> 00:17:49.187 line:15% 
I prayed, and I cried, and one day,

333
00:17:49.989 --> 00:17:53.454
I heard that the statue of the virgin of Fatima

334
00:17:53.454 --> 00:17:56.195
was traveling to Juarez.

335
00:17:56.195 --> 00:18:00.056
So I went to the church where the virgin was,

336
00:18:00.056 --> 00:18:01.336
feeling very desperate.

337
00:18:01.336 --> 00:18:06.200
I wanted to live, so when I went into the church

338
00:18:06.200 --> 00:18:09.794
where the virgin was, I prayed to her,

339
00:18:09.794 --> 00:18:12.674
and I said, "Holy mother, if you have all the power

340
00:18:12.674 --> 00:18:16.716
"that your son has, heal me, or do your will with me."

341
00:18:20.316 --> 00:18:22.859
When I did that, I felt like something was pulling my hair,

342
00:18:22.859 --> 00:18:25.781
and I felt on the right side of my face,

343
00:18:25.781 --> 00:18:27.912
I felt like something was buzzing,

344
00:18:27.912 --> 00:18:32.029
and I also felt, well, I wanted to cry,

345
00:18:32.029 --> 00:18:33.747
I wanted to scream.

346
00:18:33.747 --> 00:18:38.333
I don't know, I felt like there was an intense heat

347
00:18:38.333 --> 00:18:41.447
came into me, and they had to take me out of the church

348
00:18:41.447 --> 00:18:42.917
because I cried and I cried,

349
00:18:42.917 --> 00:18:46.329
and I kept on crying until I finally rested.

350
00:18:46.329 --> 00:18:48.869
<v Voiceover>Following this mysterious episode,</v>

351
00:18:48.869 --> 00:18:51.834
Teresa returned to her doctor, fully convinced

352
00:18:51.834 --> 00:18:54.116
that she had been healed.

353
00:18:54.116 --> 00:18:56.836
<v ->(translated) So we went back to the doctor the next day,</v>

354
00:18:56.836 --> 00:18:59.502
and I said to him that I wanted him to do

355
00:18:59.502 --> 00:19:01.294
another test on me because I felt sure

356
00:19:01.294 --> 00:19:03.140
that there was nothing wrong with me anymore.

357
00:19:03.140 --> 00:19:04.377
And he said no.

358
00:19:04.377 --> 00:19:08.099
He said that they had given me 35 radiation treatments,

359
00:19:08.099 --> 00:19:11.032
that my brain was still too inflamed.

360
00:19:11.032 --> 00:19:14.296
and he said we're not gonna find anything out

361
00:19:14.296 --> 00:19:16.760
from a test now because your brain is too inflamed.

362
00:19:16.760 --> 00:19:20.419
But I insisted so much with him that he finally

363
00:19:20.419 --> 00:19:24.472
sent me to do another test, and then when we went back

364
00:19:24.472 --> 00:19:27.053
for the results, he said to my daughter,

365
00:19:27.053 --> 00:19:28.578
"Do you know how to read in English?"

366
00:19:28.578 --> 00:19:30.540
And my daughter said, "Yeah, I do."

367
00:19:30.540 --> 00:19:33.897
And he said, "Okay, here's the envelope.

368
00:19:33.897 --> 00:19:35.315
"Open it up so that you could see

369
00:19:35.315 --> 00:19:37.171
"the results of your mother's test."

370
00:19:37.171 --> 00:19:39.571
And before she opened it, he reminded us,

371
00:19:39.571 --> 00:19:42.291
he said, "Your mother's cancer is incurable,

372
00:19:42.291 --> 00:19:44.894
"and it's throughout her whole brain."

373
00:19:44.894 --> 00:19:47.656
So my daughter opened up the envelope,

374
00:19:47.656 --> 00:19:49.416
and when she looked at the test results,

375
00:19:49.416 --> 00:19:50.900
she turned to the doctor and said,

376
00:19:50.900 --> 00:19:53.373
"Look, this test says that there's not even

377
00:19:53.373 --> 00:19:55.176
a trace of cancer left."

378
00:19:55.176 --> 00:19:56.999
And the doctor grabbed the paper,

379
00:19:56.999 --> 00:19:59.730
and he started reading it for himself.

380
00:19:59.730 --> 00:20:03.591
And he said, "Well, I, the only explanation

381
00:20:03.591 --> 00:20:06.002
"I can find for this, it just has to be a miracle

382
00:20:06.002 --> 00:20:09.649
"because I know that you had an incurable cancer.

383
00:20:09.649 --> 00:20:12.167
"There was no help for that."

384
00:20:12.167 --> 00:20:15.260
And I said, "Well, maybe for science

385
00:20:15.260 --> 00:20:18.648
"there's no answer to this, but for God, there is."

386
00:20:18.648 --> 00:20:20.386
And to me, the most important thing

387
00:20:20.386 --> 00:20:24.568
is that God has healed me, and I am healthy now.

388
00:20:27.398 --> 00:20:30.370
And I give glory to God that he healed me

389
00:20:30.370 --> 00:20:33.722
because of my faith, but you know it's because

390
00:20:33.722 --> 00:20:37.490
I placed a lot of faith in God, and I have a lot of faith

391
00:20:37.490 --> 00:20:41.244
that I'm healthy and that I'm not going to get sick agian.

392
00:20:41.244 --> 00:20:44.870
In fact, I threw out all the pills, every one.

393
00:20:44.870 --> 00:20:48.145
I'm not taking any now, and since about a year

394
00:20:48.145 --> 00:20:50.641
and four months ago, I haven't taken a thing.

395
00:20:50.641 --> 00:20:54.037
And I give glory to God because I'm fine now.

396
00:20:56.898 --> 00:20:58.892
<v ->Deborah Deckelman was a woman</v>

397
00:20:58.892 --> 00:21:00.737
facing her own emotional darkness

398
00:21:00.737 --> 00:21:04.123
when she was visited by a mysterious stranger.

399
00:21:05.911 --> 00:21:07.906
<v ->Well, my experience happened about 11 years ago,</v>

400
00:21:07.906 --> 00:21:12.906 line:15% 
and I was going through a series of tragedies in my life

401
00:21:12.993 --> 00:21:16.001 line:15% 
to where I had two close friends

402
00:21:16.001 --> 00:21:18.881
who were killed in a car accident.

403
00:21:20.681 --> 00:21:24.393
I had a miscarriage, lost my grandmother,

404
00:21:24.393 --> 00:21:29.393
and I was dealing with some joint custody problems.

405
00:21:29.833 --> 00:21:33.513
I was contemplating suicide, and it got to the point

406
00:21:33.513 --> 00:21:36.691
where I decided that the fastest way to do it

407
00:21:36.691 --> 00:21:40.531
was, would be to take the gun and shoot myself.

408
00:21:40.531 --> 00:21:45.531
But, I called my husband, he came home.

409
00:21:46.976 --> 00:21:50.194
We went into a hospital, and I was admitted there.

410
00:21:50.194 --> 00:21:53.673
It was a depression clinic, and I was always laying

411
00:21:53.673 --> 00:21:56.220
on the bed and sobbing and crying.

412
00:21:56.220 --> 00:21:57.319
My hands were over my eyes.

413
00:21:59.589 --> 00:22:02.620
I heard this beautiful voice say Deborah,

414
00:22:02.620 --> 00:22:06.086
and she said, "Can I come around and talk with you?"

415
00:22:06.086 --> 00:22:09.704
And I took my hands down, and I looked up at her,

416
00:22:09.704 --> 00:22:13.201
and I said yes, and I was still crying.

417
00:22:13.201 --> 00:22:14.524
And she came around.

418
00:22:14.524 --> 00:22:16.998
She's a grandmotherly type woman,

419
00:22:16.998 --> 00:22:19.552
and she says, "I know what you're thinking

420
00:22:19.552 --> 00:22:21.093
"and you're feeling right now."

421
00:22:21.093 --> 00:22:22.256
She says, "You're feeling like you're in this

422
00:22:22.256 --> 00:22:26.171
"pit of darkness and there's no hope for you."

423
00:22:26.171 --> 00:22:29.733
And that's what I was thinking.

424
00:22:29.733 --> 00:22:34.733
She knew me inside and out, and she says,

425
00:22:35.289 --> 00:22:38.724
"I'm here to tell you this is what God wants you to do.

426
00:22:40.074 --> 00:22:42.820
"He wants you to take it just one day at a time,

427
00:22:42.820 --> 00:22:46.777
"and scratch away at that darkness, just a little bit,

428
00:22:46.777 --> 00:22:48.893
"just scratch away just a little bit

429
00:22:48.893 --> 00:22:51.886
and you'll see this crack, and in the crack,

430
00:22:51.886 --> 00:22:54.819
"every day you do this, you'll see it open and a little

431
00:22:54.819 --> 00:22:58.627
"bit more light will come through, and everyday,

432
00:22:58.627 --> 00:23:00.964
"more and more light will come through for you."

433
00:23:00.964 --> 00:23:03.149
And she says, "Do you know what that is?"

434
00:23:03.149 --> 00:23:05.948
She said, "That is God's love and promise

435
00:23:05.948 --> 00:23:08.621
"for you that you must go on."

436
00:23:08.621 --> 00:23:12.695
She put one hand on my forehead and one on my heart,

437
00:23:12.695 --> 00:23:17.580
and as we prayed, it was like someone

438
00:23:17.580 --> 00:23:20.162
brought the sun from the sky

439
00:23:20.162 --> 00:23:23.617
and into that pit of darkness I had,

440
00:23:23.617 --> 00:23:27.500
and it was all over me, and all through me,

441
00:23:27.500 --> 00:23:30.881
and I was being embraced by God.

442
00:23:30.881 --> 00:23:34.475
I was being comforted and loved in such a way

443
00:23:34.475 --> 00:23:36.662
I had never felt before.

444
00:23:36.662 --> 00:23:40.960
And I looked up, and it was just pure light.

445
00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:43.563
My mind and my heart were healed.

446
00:23:43.563 --> 00:23:46.976
The depression was gone, totally lifted.

447
00:23:46.976 --> 00:23:51.976
She went out the door passed directly next to the nurse

448
00:23:53.055 --> 00:23:57.204
who was coming in at the time, and I asked the nurse

449
00:23:57.204 --> 00:24:01.556
who this wonderful radiant person was

450
00:24:01.556 --> 00:24:04.841
that just made me feel so loved,

451
00:24:04.841 --> 00:24:08.723
and the nurse said, "Who was who?"

452
00:24:08.723 --> 00:24:11.283
<v Voiceover>No one but Deborah had seen a woman,</v>

453
00:24:11.283 --> 00:24:13.481
and according to the hospital, she was neither

454
00:24:13.481 --> 00:24:16.937
an employee nor a volunteer.

455
00:24:16.937 --> 00:24:21.937
<v ->I got up the next morning, and I got out of bed</v>

456
00:24:22.675 --> 00:24:25.042
and I went over to the window, and I opened the blinds,

457
00:24:25.042 --> 00:24:29.160
and right there in front of me at the window

458
00:24:29.160 --> 00:24:31.741
was this big beautiful rainbow

459
00:24:31.741 --> 00:24:34.717
and the colors were so brilliant and beautiful.

460
00:24:34.717 --> 00:24:37.982
It was my confirmation that God was telling me again

461
00:24:37.982 --> 00:24:39.335
See?

462
00:24:39.335 --> 00:24:42.332
My promises are good.

463
00:24:42.332 --> 00:24:45.713
My experience lead to having forums, and it also

464
00:24:45.713 --> 00:24:48.561
brought to me many special people.

465
00:24:48.561 --> 00:24:51.196
<v Voiceover>Deborah felt compelled to share her story</v>

466
00:24:51.196 --> 00:24:52.998
with a small group.

467
00:24:52.998 --> 00:24:54.960
So many people responded with their own

468
00:24:54.960 --> 00:24:56.955 line:15% 
remarkable stories that Deborah

469
00:24:56.955 --> 00:24:58.944 line:15% 
organized a forum.

470
00:24:58.944 --> 00:25:01.776 line:15% 
<v Voiceover>On the town square in Handover, Pennsylvania,</v>

471
00:25:01.776 --> 00:25:04.571 line:15% 
in a converted store room above a gift shop

472
00:25:04.571 --> 00:25:08.859 line:15% 
called The Rose Trellis, there's a special meeting going on.

473
00:25:08.859 --> 00:25:11.119
Welcome to the second meeting of over.

474
00:25:11.119 --> 00:25:12.762
<v Voiceover>Nearly 500 people gathered</v>

475
00:25:12.762 --> 00:25:15.685
from hundreds of miles around to share their own stories,

476
00:25:15.685 --> 00:25:18.319
and to hear the experiences of others.

477
00:25:18.319 --> 00:25:21.328
One of the persons to attend Deborah's forum

478
00:25:21.328 --> 00:25:24.048
was a gentleman called Albert Gorsuch.

479
00:25:24.048 --> 00:25:27.333
He was a self-professed workaholic

480
00:25:27.333 --> 00:25:29.146
with a responsible job and a family

481
00:25:29.146 --> 00:25:32.655
that depended on him, and then he began drinking.

482
00:25:37.195 --> 00:25:39.567
<v ->I couldn't wait in the morning to start drinking,</v>

483
00:25:39.567 --> 00:25:43.757 line:15% 
and then I got into gambling,

484
00:25:45.085 --> 00:25:47.421
and so on.

485
00:25:47.421 --> 00:25:50.343
So then I, this went on for several years

486
00:25:51.623 --> 00:25:55.023
with my wife and the next morning,

487
00:25:55.023 --> 00:25:57.476
she could be out in the kitchen making breakfast,

488
00:25:57.476 --> 00:26:00.100
and she would be out there singing,

489
00:26:00.100 --> 00:26:03.864
and go on and said, "God, how can she do these things?"

490
00:26:03.864 --> 00:26:06.446
How can it be that she can do these things

491
00:26:06.446 --> 00:26:10.190
when she knew what I'd been doing?

492
00:26:10.190 --> 00:26:12.995
I would try to hide part of it from her,

493
00:26:12.995 --> 00:26:14.797
especially the gambling part.

494
00:26:16.357 --> 00:26:21.295
And one day, my boss came up and he said, "Albert."

495
00:26:21.295 --> 00:26:24.184
I had been bringing a man in two years for me

496
00:26:24.184 --> 00:26:28.431
on my job, and he said, "I can't pay

497
00:26:28.431 --> 00:26:33.431
"two of you on for this job, and I would like you to retire.

498
00:26:33.448 --> 00:26:36.028
"You're old enough to retire."

499
00:26:36.028 --> 00:26:41.028
Well, that's the day that the earth crashed around me.

500
00:26:41.287 --> 00:26:43.047
<v Voiceover>The only solution Albert could see</v>

501
00:26:43.047 --> 00:26:46.620
